<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="change-control">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>project-manager</domain>
    <summary>Route every change request through formal log, impact analysis, tiered decision, and baseline update cycle. Tier authority by size: PM approves minor, Sponsor approves medium, CCB approves major.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>change-control</tag>
      <tag>change-management</tag>
      <tag>scope</tag>
      <tag>governance</tag>
      <tag>approval</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>change</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Change Control</title>

    <summary>Route every change request through a formal log → impact analysis → tiered decision → baseline update cycle. Tier authority by size: PM approves minor (less than 1 day, less than $500), Sponsor approves medium (1-5 days, less than $5k), CCB approves major. The rule: never auto-approve — the agent prepares the impact packet; a human approver signs off before implementation begins.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Uncontrolled changes are the primary mechanism by which scope creep destroys budgets. A formal register makes every change visible and comparable, catches repeat requests (same CR under a new title), and ensures baselines (scope, schedule, budget) stay synchronized after approval. Tiering by size prevents the CCB from becoming a bottleneck that pushes stakeholders toward informal workarounds.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Fixed-scope, fixed-budget engagements (agency contracts, SoWs) where every change has billing impact.</item>
        <item>Regulated environments (finance, healthcare, government) requiring an audit trail of decisions.</item>
        <item>Projects with multiple stakeholders submitting asks via different channels — register forces one queue.</item>
        <item>Late-stage projects (greater than 50% complete) where every change has compounded ripple effects.</item>
        <item>Programs where one project's change affects sibling projects.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pure agile teams with continuous backlog refinement — change is the default state, not the exception.</item>
        <item>Discovery/research phases — you want changes; controlling them defeats the purpose.</item>
        <item>Solo projects where you are both requester and approver — capture as a TODO, not a CR.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="change-process">
      <title>Change Control Process</title>

      <section name="process-flow">
        <title>Process Flow</title>
        <p>Every change request follows: Request → Log → Analyze → Decide → Implement → Close. No step is skippable; informal approval is not approval.</p>
        <rule>
          <statement>The agent prepares the impact packet; a human approver signs off before implementation begins — never auto-approve.</statement>
          <rationale>Change approval has organizational and contractual consequences. Automated approval removes the accountability trace that auditors, sponsors, and clients require.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="decision-tier-authority">
        <title>Decision Tier Authority</title>
        <list>
          <item>Minor: less than 1 day impact, less than $500 cost → Project Manager approves.</item>
          <item>Medium: 1-5 days impact, less than $5,000 cost → Sponsor approves.</item>
          <item>Major: greater than 5 days OR greater than $5,000 OR high-risk → CCB approves.</item>
          <item>Any CR that increases risk score above threshold → CCB regardless of cost/days.</item>
        </list>
        <rule>
          <statement>Tier the process by impact size; a 2-week CCB cadence for minor changes creates informal workarounds.</statement>
          <rationale>When the formal process is too slow, requesters route around it. Informal "just do it" approvals reappear as scope creep. Minor changes approved at PM level maintain process speed without bypassing governance.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="impact-analysis-areas">
        <title>Impact Analysis Areas</title>
        <list>
          <item>Scope — what features, deliverables, or WBS elements are affected?</item>
          <item>Schedule — how many working days added or removed?</item>
          <item>Cost — what additional budget is required?</item>
          <item>Quality — does the change affect standards, testing coverage, or technical debt?</item>
          <item>Risk — what new risks does the change introduce?</item>
          <item>Resources — which team members must work on it, and what does that displace?</item>
        </list>
        <rule>
          <statement>Run impact analysis against current baselines (scope, schedule, budget), not against the original plan.</statement>
          <rationale>The original plan is stale. Impact must be measured from the current approved baseline so the delta is accurate. Comparing to the original plan understates accumulated drift.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="change-register-status">
        <title>Change Register Status Values</title>
        <list>
          <item>Submitted — received, not yet reviewed.</item>
          <item>Under Review — impact analysis in progress.</item>
          <item>Approved — will be implemented; baselines must be updated before work starts.</item>
          <item>Rejected — will not be implemented; reason documented for repeat-CR detection.</item>
          <item>Deferred — postponed to future phase or release.</item>
          <item>Implemented — completed; baseline updates verified.</item>
        </list>
        <rule>
          <statement>Track rejected CRs forever; use them to detect repeat asks and as evidence for descope discussions.</statement>
          <rationale>Rejected requests rarely die — they re-submit under a new title. A history of rejections with documented reasons allows the PM to identify repeat patterns and address the root demand.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="change-antipatterns">
      <title>Change Control Antipatterns and Agent Gotchas</title>

      <section name="process-antipatterns">
        <title>Process Antipatterns</title>
        <antipattern>
          <description>No formal process — changes happen informally via chat and verbal agreements.</description>
          <reason>Informal changes have no impact analysis, no audit trail, and no baseline update. They compound invisibly until the schedule or budget collapses with no documented cause.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>PM approves every change regardless of size, bypassing Sponsor and CCB.</description>
          <reason>PM authority is limited by tier. Overreach on major changes removes the sponsor's ability to protect the project's ROI case and creates contractual exposure.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Implementing an approved CR without updating the scope, schedule, and budget baselines simultaneously.</description>
          <reason>Baselines that lag behind approved changes make EVM calculations and future change impact analysis inaccurate. Update baselines atomically with implementation confirmation.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Rejecting changes without documenting the reason.</description>
          <reason>Undocumented rejections allow the same CR to re-appear under a different title. A rejection log with reasoning enables pattern detection and deflects repeat requests with evidence.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>

      <section name="agent-gotchas">
        <title>Agent Gotchas</title>
        <rule>
          <statement>Require the agent's impact analysis to walk specific WBS node IDs, not handwave "schedule impact".</statement>
          <rationale>LLMs underestimate ripple effects because they reason at the summary level. Walking specific WBS elements forces the agent to consider dependency chains and resource conflicts that summary-level analysis misses.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <list>
          <item>Agents recommend Option A (full implementation) by default; explicitly require ranking all options including defer and decline.</item>
          <item>Generated business justifications paraphrase the request instead of citing metrics; force quoting stakeholder evidence or measurement data.</item>
          <item>"Approval drift" via Slack threads: agent must refuse to mark a CR Approved without an explicit decision artefact (signed form, ticket transition, email sign-off).</item>
          <item>Agents merge or rebase implementation branches without confirming baseline updates; add a checklist gate before branch merge.</item>
          <item>Set a CR rate metric: greater than 1 CR/week per $1M scope = symptom of poor initial scoping; surface to sponsor rather than silently processing.</item>
          <item>Near-duplicate CRs: compare new CR against last 90 days of rejected CRs; flag similarity greater than 0.7 with prior rejection reasons.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <title>Agentic Workflow and Integration</title>
      <p>A subagent intercepts informal change asks (Slack, email), drafts a Change Request with required fields, runs impact analysis against scope/schedule/budget/risk, and routes to the correct decision tier. The agent never auto-approves — it only prepares a packet for the human approver. Maintain the change register as data (CSV/YAML); the Markdown is a generated view. Close the loop: when an approved CR is implemented, the agent updates WBS, schedule, budget baselines simultaneously to keep them in sync.</p>

      <section name="recommended-subagents">
        <title>Recommended Subagents</title>
        <list>
          <item>faion-pm-agent — drafts CRs, runs impact analysis, maintains register.</item>
          <item>faion-business-analyst — refines requirements affected by the change.</item>
          <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — opens new SDD tasks for approved CRs.</item>
          <item>improver — periodic audit: rejection-rate trend, repeat-CR detection.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="cli-tools">
        <title>CLI Tools</title>
        <list>
          <item>gh (GitHub CLI) — CRs as GitHub Issues with labels (CR/scope/cost/schedule) (https://cli.github.com).</item>
          <item>glab (GitLab CLI) — Same for GitLab Issues (https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/cli).</item>
          <item>jira (jira-cli) — CRs as Jira issue type (https://github.com/ankitpokhrel/jira-cli).</item>
          <item>yq, jq — Process register YAML/JSON (yq.dev / stedolan.github.io/jq).</item>
          <item>pandoc — Render CRs to PDF for sponsor sign-off (https://pandoc.org).</item>
          <item>gitpython — Auto-link CR to commits implementing it (https://github.com/gitpython-developers/GitPython).</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="services-apps">
        <title>Services and Apps</title>
        <list>
          <item>Jira (Change Mgmt template) — SaaS, REST API; built-in workflow, ITIL-aligned.</item>
          <item>ServiceNow Change Management — SaaS, Table API; ITIL/CAB workflow, audit-ready.</item>
          <item>Atlassian Confluence — SaaS, REST API; host change register pages.</item>
          <item>GitHub / GitLab Issues — SaaS, REST + GraphQL; CRs as labelled issues, link to PRs.</item>
          <item>Smartsheet — SaaS, REST API; common in PMOs for change log.</item>
          <item>BMC Helix Remedyforce — SaaS, REST API; heavy ITIL change.</item>
          <item>Notion / Airtable — SaaS, REST API; lightweight register.</item>
          <item>DocuSign — SaaS, REST API; electronic sign-off on major CRs.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="best-practices">
        <title>Best Practices</title>
        <list>
          <item>Tier the process: minor (PM), medium (Sponsor), major (CCB) — speed is a feature.</item>
          <item>Every CR has Options (do, partial, defer, decline) so approvers see trade-offs, not a binary.</item>
          <item>Track rejected CRs forever; use them as evidence for descope discussions and to spot repeat asks.</item>
          <item>Keep CR data colocated with code repo; PR description references CR id; commit links back.</item>
          <item>Run impact analysis against current baselines (scope, schedule, budget) — not against original plan, which is stale.</item>
          <item>Set a CR rate metric: greater than 1 CR/week per million $ scope = symptom of poor initial scoping.</item>
          <item>Link CRs to risks: a CR that increases risk score above threshold needs CCB review even if cost is small.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
        <title>AI Agent Gotchas</title>
        <list>
          <item>LLMs underestimate ripple effects; require the impact analysis to walk specific WBS nodes by id, not handwave "schedule impact".</item>
          <item>Agents tend to recommend Option A (full implementation) — explicitly require ranking and a defer/decline option.</item>
          <item>Auto-closing implemented CRs without verifying baselines were updated leaves drift; include a checklist gate.</item>
          <item>Generated business justifications often paraphrase the request — useless. Force quoting metrics or stakeholder evidence.</item>
          <item>Beware "approval drift" via long Slack threads: the agent should refuse to mark a CR Approved without an explicit decision artefact (signed form, ticket transition, email sign-off).</item>
          <item>Never let the agent merge or rebase the CR-implementation branch without sponsor confirmation in the register.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="references">
      <title>References</title>
      <list>
        <item>PMBOK Guide 7th Edition — Delivery Performance Domain &amp; Project Integration Management.</item>
        <item>ISO 21502 — Change control guidance.</item>
        <item>ITIL 4 — Change Enablement practice.</item>
        <item>PRINCE2 — Manage by Exception / Issue and Change Procedure.</item>
        <item>"Software Project Survival Guide" — Steve McConnell (Ch. on change control).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/change-request.md" purpose="CR form with description, justification, impact table, options, decision block."/>
      <template path="templates/change-register.md" purpose="Change register table for tracking all CRs."/>
    </templates>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/cr-router.py" purpose="Assign approval tier (PM/Sponsor/CCB) from impact YAML (days, cost, risk level)."/>
    </scripts>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.pmi.org/pmbok-guide"/>
      <link href="https://www.itil.org/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
